| 255.255.255.252 | /30  | 2         | 4               | 2                                       |
| 255.255.255.254 | /31  | 1         | 2               | 0* (special use â€“ point-to-point links) |
| 255.255.255.255 | /32  | 0         | 1               | 0 (single host address)                 |

 ğŸ§  Quick Trick
You can find usable IPs/hosts instantly from the CIDR:
Usable ip = (2^(32 - CIDR)) - 2     OR     Usable ip = (2^Host Bits) - 2  

Subnetting 
Subnetting means dividing a large network into smaller, more manageable sub-networks (subnets).
Barrowing Host Bit to Network bit.

ğŸ§© The Goal
Weâ€™re given how many hosts we need per subnet â€”
and we must find:
# The subnet mask (/CIDR)
# The number of subnets
# The usable IP range

ğŸ§® Example 1 â€” Class C Network (192.168.1.0/24) Requirement: 20 hosts per subnet

Step 1 â†’ Formula  2^h âˆ’ 2 â‰¥ 20
Try values:
2â´ âˆ’ 2 = 14 âŒ (too few)
2âµ âˆ’ 2 = 30 âœ… (enough)
So h = 5

Step 2 â†’ New Prefix
192.168.1.0 => In Class-C 3 network bit and 1 host bit N|N|N|H
Convert Host Bit to Binary 
192.168.1.00000000 <= COUNT 5 (h=5) from this direction & handover the rest of the bits to Network
192.168.1.11100000 ( Network bit is represented by 1 and host bit is represented by 0)
 Conver into decimal value  (128+64+32=224)
192.168.1.224/27  

New Prefix => 32âˆ’5=27 => IP4 is 32 bit in this 5 bits is host bit, So now we have 27 bits with network

2â·  2â¶ 2âµ 2â´ 2Â³ 2Â² 2Â¹ 2â°    		âœ… (anything to the power 0 = 1)
128 64 32 16 8  4  2  1

âœ… New subnet mask = 255.255.255.224 (/27)    Note: Subnet Mask - Change the network bit to 255 and host bit to 0

Step 3 â†’ Number of Subnets
==========================
We borrowed 3 bits (from /24 â†’ /27) 2^3=8 subnets

Step 4 â†’ Block Size
==================
256âˆ’224=32
So each subnet has 32 addresses.

Step 5 â†’ Subnets and Ranges
